authorMeta.name: timothy_bramlett
text:
What is an LLM? Let me break it down.

LLM stands for Large Language Model. It's the technology behind ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini.

Think of it like this. An LLM has read basically the entire internet. Books, articles, code, conversations. Trillions and trillions of words.

From all that reading, it learned patterns. How sentences flow. How ideas connect. How to answer questions. When you type something, it predicts the most likely next word, over and over, until you get a response. It's pattern matching at an insane scale.

But here's what gets interesting. Scale it up past 100 billion parameters and it starts doing things nobody programmed it to do. Scientists call these emergent capabilities. Force it to think step by step and something changes. Researchers are still debating whether that's actual reasoning or just really convincing pattern matching.

But all of this is what an LLM is.

This is part of a new series where I'm explaining common tech terms. Follow along for more.

It's normal being imperfect. And not knowing it all. üòâ (Even AI doesn't know it all)

‚ÄúLife is not always perfect. Like a road, it has many bends, ups and down, but that‚Äôs its beauty.‚Äù
‚Äï Amit Ray

Just wanted to share this as social media often shows that we must know everything as a programmer and we must be extremely good and know it all. But actually you do not need to know everything to be a good programmer. I've worked with many amazing programmers with 20+ years experience and they don't know it all either. They often don't know what they are doing. They often don't know what algorithm is best to use. They often don't know what the best answer is to a question. It's totally normal.

All it takes is building experience so you'll be able to get to an answer faster than you used to be. It does not mean you need to have an answer ready all the time. üòâ

But also with things like procrastinating, losing focus, starting one to many side project and not finishing projects. It's all normal and often just part of doing something you like doing. üôå

As with starting too many projects, it's actually a good thing. It means you are driven and excited about what you do. It keeps the spark alive and that will help you grow. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Don't let social media fool you that you must be a genius to be a great programmer and game developer. Just know that all that matters is that you enjoy what you do. And that you are human. üòâ

üîç What Kling AI Is
	‚Ä¢	AI video generator: You write a natural language prompt (a description of what you want to see), and Kling AI generates a short video based on that description.  
	‚Ä¢	Developed by Kuaishou: A Beijing-based tech company known for its social and video apps.  
	‚Ä¢	Part of a broader creative ecosystem: It‚Äôs similar in purpose to other AI text-to-video tools like OpenAI‚Äôs Sora or Google‚Äôs Veo, but with its own strengths and limitations.  

üé¨ Key Capabilities
	‚Ä¢	Text-to-Video: Generates short clips from your written descriptions (prompts).  
	‚Ä¢	Image-to-Video / Video Expansions: Some versions can extend or animate existing images or video references.  
	‚Ä¢	Different models / versions: Over time, Kling has released several versions (e.g., 1.6, 2.0, 2.1 and newer 3.0 engines) with improvements in video quality, motion realism, and creative control.  

üß† How It Works (High Level)

Under the hood, Kling AI uses deep learning and generative models (such as transformer and diffusion-based architectures) that learn patterns of motion, scene layout, textures, and timing from lots of video data. These AI systems predict frame sequences that match the conditions you describe in your prompt.  

üìå Considerations
	‚Ä¢	Not a full video editor: It doesn‚Äôt replace traditional video editing software ‚Äî you get generated clips, not a full editing suite.  
	‚Ä¢	Content moderation: It applies strict filtering on sensitive or restricted content in line with its policies.  
	‚Ä¢	Availability and quality vary: The platform started in China and later expanded globally, and users‚Äô experiences (in terms of quality, speed, and subscription details) can differ.  

In short: Kling AI is an advanced AI video generation tool that turns text (and sometimes images) into short video clips using deep learning ‚Äî useful for creators, marketers, and storytellers who want quick AI-assisted visual content.

authorMeta.name: sam869939
text:
LLMs are deterministic - given the same input, they always output the same probability distribution over all possible next tokens. The ‚Äúrandomness‚Äù only happens when we sample a single token from that distribution.
Temperature reshapes probabilities before sampling. Lower values (0.1) concentrate on likely tokens, higher values (2.0) flatten the distribution. Temperature = 0 is deterministic (always picks the most probable token).
Top-k samples only from the k most probable tokens.
Top-p (nucleus) dynamically samples from the smallest set of tokens whose cumulative probability exceeds p - adaptive based on the model‚Äôs ‚Äúconfidence.‚Äù
These can be combined (e.g., top-p then temperature). The randomness comes from the pseudo-random sampling step, which is why setting a seed makes outputs reproducible.

- Lets you toggle editing on and off anytime
- Works across all major browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge)
- Great for quick content mockups and experimenting with UI ideas

authorMeta.name: timothy_bramlett
text:
What is an LLM? Let me break it down.

LLM stands for Large Language Model. It's the technology behind ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini.

Think of it like this. An LLM has read basically the entire internet. Books, articles, code, conversations. Trillions and trillions of words.

From all that reading, it learned patterns. How sentences flow. How ideas connect. How to answer questions. When you type something, it predicts the most likely next word, over and over, until you get a response. It's pattern matching at an insane scale.

But here's what gets interesting. Scale it up past 100 billion parameters and it starts doing things nobody programmed it to do. Scientists call these emergent capabilities. Force it to think step by step and something changes. Researchers are still debating whether that's actual reasoning or just really convincing pattern matching.

But all of this is what an LLM is.

This is part of a new series where I'm explaining common tech terms. Follow along for more.
